data <- read_csv('data/CleanedData.csv')

  • response variable has 1 upper outlier that may be problematic
data %>%
  ggplot(aes(ph)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=30)

  • nothing special out distributions, other than the obvious outlier point mentioned previously
data %>%
  gather(key='key', value='value', -ph) %>%
  ggplot(aes(value, ph)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~key, ncol=4, scales='free') +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank()
        )

  • only one near zero variance predictor. doesn’t look too terrible from distribution
caret::nearZeroVar(data, names=TRUE)
## [1] "hydpressure1"
data %>%
  ggplot(aes(hydpressure1)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=20)

  • suggest removing one upper outlier
data <- data %>%
  filter(ph < 9)
  • split into training/testing
set.seed(123)

part <- caret::createDataPartition(data$ph, p=0.8, list=FALSE)
training <- data %>%
  filter(row_number() %in% part)
testing <- data %>%
  filter(!row_number() %in% part)
  • write out for further processing
training %>%
  write_csv('./data/training.csv')

testing %>%
  write_csv('./data/testing.csv')
